text: The Constitution of the Friendly Farmers Community
Ratified by the Community on the _ of January, 2024.

We, the Neighbors of the Friendly Farmers Community, in order to be the most Friendly, most Active, most Remarkable, most Munificent, and most Sustainable farmers in Hay Day, do ordain and establish this new Constitution in order to govern all Neighborhoods and Neighbors of our Community by retaining the most successful aspects of our original Constitution and altering the other elements in a way that better suits a multi-Neighborhood collective.

From the Neighborhoods of Friendly Farmers shall be established a Grand Council. This Council shall be made up of Neighbors from each Neighborhood, who together serve as the primary leadership of the Community. They shall work to construct and enforce rules across all of the Neighborhoods, pursue the general success of each, and oversee necessary managerial tasks.

All Members of the Council shall be given the space to be heard and considered in discussion and decision making. All shall be able to use their own good judgment in enforcing rules, in contributing to discussion, and in issuing their votes in Council matters.

Council Member farms are to be given Coleader or Leader status in-game in the Neighborhoods in which they have Council authority; no other Neighbors shall be given such. Farms given Leader must belong to an Untermed Seat holder.
The Council shall be made up of two types of Seats: Termed and Untermed.

The Council shall be allocated two Termed Seats for each Neighborhood of the Community, which are to be held by Neighbors elected from the respective Neighborhood. Council Members holding these Seats shall be split into four Ranks, I-IV. The Termed Seats corresponding to a given Neighborhood can hold Council Members of any combination of the Ranks, except only one of its Seats can be held by a Senior Member of the Council.

The Council shall also be allocated one Untermed Seat for each Neighborhood of the Community, plus one. Council Members holding these Seats are split into the Ranks of Head Seat and Permanent Member. Untermed Seats are filled if and when someone earns them through promotion; they do not have to be filled as long as there is at least one Head Seat.
The Council shall consist of two membership distinctions: the Senior Members of the Council and the Junior Members of the Council.

Termed Seat holders of Rank I, Rank II, and Rank III shall be classified as Junior Members of the Council. Junior Members only have Council-authority (the right to hold a coleadership position, and exercise the abilities thereof) within the Neighborhood that they were elected from; however, this shall not be construed as to reduce their ability to carry out Council duties for the other Neighborhoods or Community at large that do not require any particular powers other than simply holding a Council Seat. Junior Members shall not communicate on behalf of the Council with anyone outside of the Community.

All Untermed Seat holders and Rank IV Members holding Termed Seats shall be classified as Senior Members of the Council. Senior Members shall have Council-authority (leader/coleadership) in all of the Neighborhoods that they themselves are in. They shall also be able to communicate on behalf of the Council with foreign leaders, players, or entities, where such communication is disclosed with and approved by the Council. The Senior Members shall also hold specific constitutional duties and abilities, as defined in This.

The Rank within the Council that a Council Member has relates primarily to their term length and to whether they are classified as Junior or Senior. A Council Member’s position should not affect their ability to contribute to Council activity or discussion except where specific Council Members have specific powers or duties defined in This. Any further limitations shall be prohibited, except the Council may prescribe by law reasonable limitations on access to resources or power for Rank I Members in order to aid a smooth transition of power.

When a Neighbor is first elected to the Council, they shall serve as a Rank I Member. If a previous Council Member rejoins the Council at a later time, the Senior Members of the Council may vote to reinstate the Rank immediately below their most recently held Rank with a majority vote. Otherwise, they shall serve as a Rank I Member.
Rank I is the lowest Rank for a Council Member. They shall serve a term of one month from the point of gaining their Council membership.

Rank II is the next potential position for a Council Member to be promoted to. This is attained automatically if a Rank I Member wins and accepts renewed Council membership in election at the end of their term. This Council Member serves a term of two months from the point of their most recent reelection.

Rank III is the next potential position for a Council Member to be promoted to. This is attained automatically if a Rank II Member wins and accepts renewed Council membership in election at the end of their term. This Council Member serves a term of three months from the point of their most recent reelection.

Rank IV is the next potential position for a Council Member to be promoted to. This is attainable if a Rank III Member wins and accepts renewed Council membership in election at the end of their term. However, there are three more considerations than just this. 1. If there is already a Senior Member holding one of the Termed Seats of that Neighborhood, another cannot be promoted. 2. The candidate must also pass, with at least eighty percent accuracy, a brief, untimed constitutional literacy assessment, which shall be written fairly by the Head Seat(s). The candidate may have open access to this document for that assessment and they may take it as many times as desired, but they shall not receive direct help while taking it from any other Council Member. 3. Finally, the candidate must receive a majority of the existing Senior Members’ votes in favor of their promotion. This vote may be held once per term of the Rank III Member after the previous considerations are met.

Once the conditions are met, the candidate is promoted. This Council Member serves a term of four months from the point of their most recent reelection. If the candidate does not meet these considerations, they shall continuously serve as a Rank III Member, even after continual reelection, until the considerations are met.

If an existing Rank IV Member wishes to give up their Rank for a Rank III Member of the same Neighborhood, they may declare so. In this case, if the other promotion considerations are met, the two Council Members shall switch Seat and Rank.

A Permanent Member shall serve Council indefinitely until resignation or until demotion by the Council. This promotion is attainable by any Rank IV Council Member, and the considerations are as follows. 1. There must be an available Untermed Seat to be promoted into. 2. The Rank IV Member must have served the Council for at least 12 months. 3. Finally, the candidate must receive unanimous votes from the existing Untermed Seat holders and at least eighty percent of the whole Council’s votes in favor of their promotion. This vote may be held once per term of the Rank IV Member after the previous conditions are met.

Once the conditions are met, the candidate is promoted to fill an empty Untermed Seat and vacate their Termed Seat. If a Rank IV Member does not meet these considerations, they shall continuously serve as a Rank IV Member, even after continual reelection, until the considerations are met.

If a Permanent Member wishes to give up their Seat for a Rank IV Member, they may declare so. In this case, if the other promotion considerations are met, the two Council Members shall switch Seats and Rank.

If an Untermed Seat opens and multiple Rank IV Members have served long enough to be potential candidates for promotion to Permanent Member, the existing Untermed Seat holders must come to a consensus on an order in which for the Council to consider them.

A Head Seat serves indefinitely until resignation. There must always be at least one reigning Head Seat; in the case of the resignation of the only Head Seat, they shall either choose a successor or, if none is chosen, the position shall be automatically filled by the longest serving Council Member of the next highest Rank.
This promotion is attainable for any Permanent Member with the same considerations as promotion to Permanent Member, if an existing Head Seat nominates them for that promotion.

In the event that an Untermed Seat holder is demoted or wishes to resign to a Termed Seat, they can serve as an additional, indefinite Junior Member for one of the Neighborhoods that they are in. This shall require a majority of Council support and lasts until either a vacancy occurs in one of the regular Termed Seats of that Neighborhood, in which case they shall fill that Seat, or until they resign or are otherwise removed from Council.

An Untermed Seat holder can declare themself on an extended break, without resignation, at which point they shall be relieved of their duties and vote for the duration of that break, which shall be reinstated upon their declared return. If the sole Head Seat should declare themself on such a break, they shall choose an Acting Head Seat to take up their duties until their declared return.

If any Council Member appears to be missing in action — that is, they have taken an unexpected absence of over 2 weeks during which no player or other Council Member has been able to successfully make contact with them — they may be relieved of their duties and vote, and their term frozen, by the Head Seat(s) until their return. If no return is made within two weeks from the point at which they were relieved, they shall automatically be expelled from the Council.

In emergency cases, such as gross misconduct that is an immediate threat to a Neighbor, a Neighborhood, or the Community, a Permanent Member or Head Seat may choose to limit a lower Council Member’s access to power. Within one day, the Council must vote on Expulsion to remove the Council Member fully, or else reinstate their power.

Each Council Member shall have the authority to make decisions when carrying out their duties based on their good judgment; however, they shall seek Council input whenever desired or when such judgment may be particularly contentious. The Council may also choose to vote on new policy or on a course of action, and should when a consensus cannot easily be reached.

The Council shall respect the outcome of any vote. However, the Senior Members may vote to overrule any vote of the Council with eighty percent of Senior Members voting to do so, if less than eighty percent of Council Members originally voted in favor of the ruling.

In the case of a tied vote where a decision must be made, the Council can break ties within the Neighborhood or within the Community; the Senior Members can break ties within the Council; the Untermed Seat holders within the Senior Members; and the Head Seat(s) within the Untermed Seat holders.
If a Council Member leaves the Council during any vote, theirs must be discarded.
When creating new policies, the Council may simply come to a consensus or write the policy into law via the process herein laid out.

New policies that impact a Neighbor’s standing — for example: considerations for joining, and the grounds for demotion, kicking, or promotion — must be defined by law. Other policies too may be defined by law at the Council’s discretion. A record of the currently active laws shall be easily accessible by all Neighbors.

Once seconded, a bill shall pass into law in either of these two cases: • With at least sixty percent of the Council’s support. • With at least eighty percent of all submitted votes in favor after three days, as long as a majority of the Council has issued votes.
Laws that increase requirements or penalties for derby performance may only take effect after one full derby has elapsed since the law’s passing.
The Council must not prevent a Neighbor from opting out in derby from time to time, although reasonable restrictions may be placed on the frequency of such.

It may be beneficial for the Council to collect and distribute in-game resources (it shall not be permitted for the Council to collect or distribute out-of-game resources). Any resource that is collected in part or whole via involuntary means — e.g. at threat of demotion, kick, or other punishment — must be managed by the Council Treasury.

All manners of collection and distribution of Treasury resources must be detailed in full by law. Only Senior Members of the Council shall be able to hold these resources until usage. The Council must take detailed public record of the Treasury’s holdings. Detailed information on the collection and distribution of Treasury holdings shall be publicly available.
The Council shall be able to prescribe by law how to distribute the Elder and Member statuses in-game.

The Council shall not create any policy that discriminates against any player or favors any player based on factors of themself unrelated to their ability to contribute to their Neighborhood or the Community.
Any policy that can be equally applied to Council Members as Neighbors without affecting their ability to carry out Council duties must apply equally to both.

A Rank IV Member or Permanent Member can be demoted to the next highest Rank or expelled from Council with a Vote of Demotion. Any Council Member, except for a Head Seat, can be expelled with a Vote of Expulsion. Both require eighty percent of the Council’s support.

A Council Member or previous Council Member convicted of treason can never serve again on Council. A player can be convicted of treason with eighty percent of the Council’s support if the player, while serving as a Council Member, acted in one of the following ways or aided/abetted someone else in acting in one of the following ways: • Aiding a Neighborhood outside of the Community in a way that directly harms Friendly Farmers. Examples of such may include, but are not limited to: stealing players, taking resources, leaking secrets, or sharing private Council chat. • Refusing to peacefully transfer Council power or resources in the case of demotion. • Coercing a Council Member or Neighbor to vote in a certain way or support a certain cause.

Council Members are elected to hold a Termed Seat by winning the vote for the prestigious FARMS Award (Friendly Active Remarkable Munificent and Sustainable). This shall be a process carried out by the Head Seat(s). The vote for the FARMS Award winner shall take place over at least five full days.

Anyone in the Neighborhood of the Seat up for election shall be eligible to vote for and be nominated for the FARMS Award. At least 4 nominees for the Award should be chosen, one of whom should be the incumbent Council Member of that Seat if applicable. The Council shall determine by law how the other three are chosen, but the method must seek to choose the best possible candidates; at least 1 nominee must be chosen by someone not presently a Council Member. Nominators should always be given ample time to make a selection.

Eligible voters shall be asked to vote for the most Friendly, Active, Remarkable, Munificent, Sustainable nominee. After the election concludes, the nominee with the most votes shall be rewarded with the FARMS Award, and asked if they would like to accept their promotion or renewed Council membership, which they shall have at least 24 hours to do. If they decline or fail to accept, the promotion shall fall onto the second highest vote receiver who shall be given the same invitation, and onto the third if needed, and so on.
Seat Change Days, on which a Seat may be exchanged, filled, or renewed, following its associated election, shall occur on the first and sixteenth of each month.

For elections corresponding to a currently filled Seat, the election must be scheduled to take place prior to the Seat Change Day that aligns with the end of the Seat holder’s term; or prior to the immediate next Seat Change Day.

An election should not be scheduled such that the winner has to wait more than two weeks for the corresponding Seat Change Day. No more than one election within a Neighborhood may be scheduled to end preceding the same Seat Change Day.

If a Council Member resigns, or a Seat is otherwise unexpectedly empty – such as if no nominee for the FARMS Award vote accepts their invitation to join the Council – either of the following two cases may apply: 1. If this shall occur within two weeks of the most recent election corresponding to that Seat, the Senior Members may choose a Neighbor to invite to fill the Seat as a Rank I Member with a majority vote. 2. Otherwise, an election shall be held immediately or delayed up to one month in order to fill the Seat.

If the holder of a Termed Seat of a given Neighborhood wishes to swap to a Termed Seat of one of the other Neighborhoods they are in, they may forfeit their Seat and thus become eligible to be nominated for an election in the other Neighborhood. However, if they are a Rank II Member or higher, they may become an additional nominee for the FARMS Award vote in the Neighborhood they seek to join without resigning. In the latter case, if they win the election, they can fill the corresponding Seat, vacate their previous Seat, and presume the Rank immediately below their previously held Rank.

A Neighborhood can be created by the Council, or an existing can be admitted to the Community. This can occur with at least eighty percent of the Council’s vote in favor and unanimous votes from the Senior Members. The Council shall have direct authority over this newly admitted Neighborhood, and it must conform to This. All players with a farm within this Neighborhood shall be considered Neighbors.

When a Neighborhood is granted Community membership, the first election of its first Termed Seat shall occur the month following its gaining membership, and the first election of its second Termed Seat shall occur the month after that.

In the event of the removal of a Neighborhood from the Community, and thus a reduction in the number of available Untermed Seats, if all Untermed Seats are already filled, then it shall be permissible to keep an extra Untermed Seat until one is vacated.

A Neighborhood can also be created or admitted to the Community that serves as a colony instead of a full membership Neighborhood. The Council would have direct authority over this Neighborhood, but the Council can determine how to structure that Neighborhood’s leadership, including granting it up to one Seat in the Council. It shall not contribute to the number of Untermed Seats within the Council, and its Council Member, if applicable, shall not be able to attain any Rank of Senior Member status.
A Neighborhood can be removed from the Community with eighty percent of the Council’s vote in favor and unanimous votes from the Senior Members of the Council.

The current Neighborhoods of Friendly Farmers under the previous Constitution: Friendly Farmers; Friendly Farmers Junior; Friendly Farmers Resort; Friendly Farmers Pro; and Friendly Farmers Garden shall be a part of the Friendly Farmers Community at the time of the ratification of This. Any player belonging to one of these Neighborhoods shall be considered a Neighbor.

The Council at the time of the ratification of This shall transition smoothly into conforming to it. The current Head Seat shall serve as a Head Seat as of the ratification of This. The current Permanent Members shall serve as Permanent Members. All of these Council Members must pass the Senior Member constitutional literacy assessment within two weeks to retain their position.

For each Neighborhood, the longer-serving of the two (if there are two) Termed Seat holders shall serve as a Rank III Member; the other should serve as a Rank II Member. If there is only one currently serving, they shall serve as Rank II Member.

For any of the just mentioned Termed Seat holders, their term shall be treated as having started on January 1st, 2024, unless their term under the previous Constitution was over half completed at the time of the ratification of This, in which case they shall serve half of a term in their new position, also starting January 1st.
The term of any Council Member elected to a Termed Seat under This before February 10th, 2024 shall be treated as having started on February 1st, 2024.
The previous Constitution shall be invalidated as of the ratification of This.
Any bill passed before the ratification of This shall be invalidated one week after the ratification of This.

This shall enter the ratification process should eighty percent of the current Council vote in favor of passing it. The ratification of This shall be complete and its articles immediately effective after either two thirds of all Community Neighbors vote in favor of ratifying it, or less than one third of all Community Neighbors vote against ratifying it after seven full days. The Council may pass bills into law under This during its ratification which may go into effect as soon as its ratification is complete.
The Council may draft and pass, with an eighty percent vote, amendments to This, which shall become ratified under the same process as This.
